\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ferroelectric field effect transistors (FeFETs, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:FeFETs"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) are a natural evolution to field effect transistors (FET), providing a
 means of maintaining the transistor state without the need for a constant
 gate voltage.
 Typically this is achieved as a standard FET with a ferroelectric replacing
 gate dielectric.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dunkel2017afefet,si2018ferroelectric"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 Further engineering for use in devices like ferroelectric random access
 memory add a metal layer in between the ferroelectric and channel to enhance
 the field, and adapt the FinFET design to utilize this design.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "khan2020thefuture"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 FeFET commercialization, in FRAM and beyond, still faces many engineering
 challenges including retention duration, finding an optimal coercive field
 and polarization strength, leakage current through the ferroelectric dielectric
, material interface mismatches, limits to minimization of the ferroelectric.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "khan2020thefuture,ma2002whyis"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 With the discovery of conductive ferroelectric compounds, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Polar-metals"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we can construct a new variation of the FeFET, where the ferroelectric
 acts the role of the semiconductor device channel.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "si2019aferroelectric"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 Ferroelectric semiconductor field effect transistors (FeSmFETs) opens up
 many new possibilities for future devices and may one day answer the aforementi
oned obstacles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 2017 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{\ensuremath{\alpha}(3R)-}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{\ensuremath{\beta}-In}_{2}\textrm{Se}_{3}$
\end_inset

 were first predicted to be ferroelectric down to one unit cell.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ding2017prediction"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{\ensuremath{\alpha}-}$
\end_inset

phase prediction indicated a combined binary in-plane (IP) and out-of-plane
 (OOP) polarization as the selenium atom shifted in the lattice, while the
 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{\ensuremath{\beta}-}$
\end_inset

phase showed only binary IP polarization.
 Due to the conductive nature of polar metals it is difficult to preform
 traditional capacitance-polarization methods on a crystal as much of the
 capacitance voltage simply leaks though the material.
 In lieu of those measurements many distinct experiments form a pool of
 evidence for the existence of ferroelectricity in 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{\ensuremath{\alpha}-In}_{2}\textrm{Se}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Second harmonic generation (SHG) shows a breaking of inversion symmetry
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dai2020intrinsic,xiao2018intrinsic,zhou2017outofplane"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, a necessary requirement for ferroelectricity.
 Piezoelectric force microscopy (PFM) has also shown evidence supporting
 ferroelectricity
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cui2018intercorrelated,wan2018roomtemperature,hou2019alphaintextrm2setextrm3,hou2019resistive,dai2020intrinsic"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, though PFM can often give false positives as similar responses arise from
 other phenomena.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vasudevan2017ferroelectric"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 To counter this some authors have looked at both IP and OOP PFM response
 correlation
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hou2019alphaintextrm2setextrm3,dai2020intrinsic,hou2019resistive,xiao2018intrinsic,cui2018intercorrelated,liu2019atomically"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, as well as observing the effect IP electric fields to alter the OOP polarizati
on measured by PFM
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hou2019alphaintextrm2setextrm3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, narrowing the possibilities of what may be producing false positives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The largest experimental verification of ferroelectricity in 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{\ensuremath{\alpha}-In}_{2}\textrm{Se}_{3}$
\end_inset

 comes from several disparate devices designs that show signs of polarization.
 The most explicit example was from an 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{\ensuremath{\alpha}-In}_{2}\textrm{Se}_{3}$
\end_inset

/graphene heterostructure FET.
 The graphene channel fermi-level shifts from the electric field produced
 by the FET gate and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{\ensuremath{\alpha}-In}_{2}\textrm{Se}_{3}$
\end_inset

 polarization, forming two peaks in the channel resistance as gate voltage
 is swept and the fermi-level passes though the charge neutral point.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wan2019nonvolatile"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 The authors use this to estimate a polarization value of 0.92 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mu C/cm^{2}}$
\end_inset

, similar to the original theoretical prediction of 0.6 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mu C/cm^{2}}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ding2017prediction"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Extensive work has been carried out by multiple group using 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{\ensuremath{\alpha}-In}_{2}\textrm{Se}_{3}$
\end_inset

 to create IP
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dai2020intrinsic,cui2018intercorrelated,hou2019resistive"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and OOP
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wan2018roomtemperature,yang2019nonvolatile"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 rectifying devices.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{DS}$
\end_inset

 sweeps below the coercive field threshold, the devices act as a typical
 semiconductor channel.
 Above the threshold voltage the device current shows a significant change
 in slope, and a large hysteresis between increasing and decreasing voltage
 sweeps, see figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:In2Se3-SampleA-I_DSvV_DS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

c and f.
 Finally, the recent pioneering of the first FeSmFET using thin crystals
 of
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{\ensuremath{\alpha}-In}_{2}\textrm{Se}_{3}$
\end_inset

 with gate dielectric of 90-nm-thick 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{SiO_{2}}$
\end_inset

 or 15-nm-thick 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{HfO_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 When gated, the channel current showed a large hysteresis, forming clockwise
 and counterclockwise loops with the respective gate dielectric, and persisting
 down to liquid helium temperatures.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "si2019aferroelectric"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Below we discuss the manufacture and measurement of similar 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{\ensuremath{\alpha}-In}_{2}\textrm{Se}_{3}$
\end_inset

 FeSmFET devices that show a metallic transition when gated though a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{SiO_{2}}$
\end_inset

 dialectic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Device manufacture
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thin crystals of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{\ensuremath{\alpha}-In}_{2}\textrm{Se}_{3}$
\end_inset

 were grown by a modified Bridgman method.
 Transport measurements were carried out on both bulk and thin mechanically-exfo
liated crystals.
 For bulk resistivity measurements, silver paint was used to form conductive
 terminals.
 In-plane resistivity measurements were carried out using a hall bar pattern
 along the longest axis of the bulk crystal.
 For out-of-plane measurements, to ensure a fresh surface, the previous
 leads were removed with a razor before new leads were added on.
 A modified four-point pattern was used to accommodate the thin c-axis of
 the crystal: a current lead was placed in the center of the crystal on
 the opposing sides of the c-axis with a voltage lead encircling each current
 lead.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Flakes of thin crystals of 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{\ensuremath{\alpha}-In}_{2}\textrm{Se}_{3}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Si:P/Si}\textrm{O}_{2}$
\end_inset

 were manufactured using mechanical exfoliation as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Mechanical-flake-exfoliation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Flakes were identified using an optical microscope and atomic force microscopy
 was used to establish a rough microscope color code to judge the thickness
 of the flakes.
 Below 20nm, flakes hue was unchanged but appeared increasingly transparent
 as thickness decreased.
 To promote better van der Walls adhesion of the flake to the substrate,
 the latter was first cleaned in Nanostrip, Acetone, 2-Proponal, and DI-water,
 before flake exfoliation, and the substrate was heated to 100C while in
 contact with the tape prior to the final removal.
 After optical identification, flake-substrates were kept in a drybox, or
 later in vacuum, to avoid water contamination and oxidation.
 
\end_layout

